That Tranio should answer the question of the money-lender with another question seems specially suitable: cf. note on the interrogative character of quin with the imperative, 172.

574-610. In 574—592 Tranio tries to get rid of the danista by coaxing him, and promises to pay first the interest ( faenus 580), and then the capital (sors 592), hoping that by this pretext he may gain time. In 593 he adopts an abusive and threatening tone, and refuses to pay the interest, holding out subsequently (599), as a sop, the promise of paying the sors ε after 600 he loses his temper and defies his opponent until Theor. interferes (610).
